message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms suggest that the left hemicord of the spinal cord was damaged. The left lower body muscle weakness and impaired vibration and proprioception in the left leg indicate damage to the left side of the spinal cord, while the loss of pain and temperature sensation in the right leg indicates damage to the right side of the spinal cord. The central cord syndrome would likely present differently, and the posterior cord is not involved in motor function.

We refer to the anatomy of the spinal cord for help. The symptoms suggest that the patient has Brown-Séquard syndrome, which is caused by damage to one side of the spinal cord. This would result in motor weakness and loss of vibration and proprioception on the same side as the injury (left in this case) and loss of pain and temperature sensation on the opposite side (right in this case), indicating damage to the left hemicord.

The metal rod entered the back at the level of T9, which corresponds to the area supplied by the left hemicord. Therefore, the most likely section of the spinal cord that was damaged in this patient is the left hemicord.

The symptoms of muscle weakness in the entire left lower body, impaired vibration, and proprioception in the left leg, as well as loss of pain and temperature sensation in the right leg, suggest a left hemicord injury. A central cord injury would typically cause upper limb weakness and bladder dysfunction, while a posterior cord injury would mainly affect sensory function. A right hemicord injury would cause right-sided motor and sensory deficits.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms presented are consistent with the Brown-Séquard syndrome, which is caused by an injury to one half of the spinal cord. In this case, the metal rod most likely caused damage to the left hemicord of the spinal cord, which explains the weakness and loss of sensation on the corresponding side of the body. Central cord syndrome typically affects the upper extremities more than the lower extremities and posterior cord syndrome typically results in loss of sensation, but not weakness.

The left lower body weakness and left leg proprioception and vibration loss indicate damage to the left hemicord, while the right leg pain and temperature loss indicate damage to the opposite (right) hemicord. The other options (central cord, posterior cord) do not fit these symptoms.
